a curated OpenAssistant test set and demonstrate that our presented methods with semantic embeddings calculated from LLMs are superior to conventional metrics on evaluating ASR performance towards LLM based voice assistants.\n\n`@inproceedings{liu24c_interspeech,\ntitle = {{Evaluating Speech Recognition Performance Towards Large Language Model Based Voice Assistants}},\nauthor = {Zhe Liu and Suyoun Kim and Ozlem Kalinli},\nyear = {2024},\nbooktitle = {{Interspeech 2024}},\npages = {4099--4103},\ndoi = {10.21437/Interspeech.2024-635},\nissn = {2958-1796},\n}`\n\n**Cite as**: Liu, Z., Kim, S., Kalinli, O. (2024) Evaluating Speech Recognition Performance Towards Large Language Model Based Voice Assistants. Proc. Interspeech 2024, 4099-4103, doi: 10.21437/Interspeech.2024-635"}, {"url": "https://www.themoonlight.io/en/review/laser-an-llm-based-asr-scoring-and-evaluation-rubric", "title": "[Literature Review] LASER: An LLM-based ASR Scoring and Evaluation Rubric", "content": "`paas wala`\n`paaswala`\n`ayskrim`\n`aaiskrim`\n\nLASER leverages the in-context learning capabilities of Large Language Models (LLMs) to provide a nuanced evaluation. The core methodology involves a carefully designed scoring rubric that classifies ASR transcription errors into three categories:\n\n`sundar`\n`sundar`\n`na`\n\nThe sentence-level LASER score is calculated using the formula:\n$\\text{Score} = 1 - \\frac{\\text{Total penalty}}{\\text{Number of reference words}}$\nwhere `Total penalty` is the sum of penalties (0 for no-penalty errors, 0.5 for minor, 1 for major) for all mismatches, and `Number of reference words` is the word count of the original reference sentence.\n\n`Total penalty`\n`Number of reference words` [...] `(Word count of original sentence; list of non-penalizable errors; list of major penalizable errors; list of minor penalizable errors; total penalty; score)`\n\nThe system was evaluated using a subset of the IndicVoices test set, encompassing Hindi, Marathi (Indo-Aryan), Malayalam, and Kannada (Dravidian) languages, with ASR predictions generated by SeamlessM4T. Human annotators, provided with the same instructions and examples, generated ground-truth penalty scores for correlation analysis.\n\nKey Results: [...] The paper introduces LASER (LLM-based ASR Scoring and Evaluation Rubric), a novel metric designed to address the limitations of traditional Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) evaluation metrics like Word Error Rate (WER). WER often unfairly penalizes morphologically and syntactically diverse errors that do not significantly alter the semantic meaning of a sentence. This issue is particularly pronounced in morphologically rich Indian languages, where WER struggles with inflectional variants, compound word representations (e.g., `paas wala` vs. `paaswala`), alternate transliterations (e.g., `ayskrim` vs. `aaiskrim`), colloquialisms, abbreviations, and numerical phrases. Existing semantic metrics like BERTScore or SemDist, and phonetic metrics like PER, also fall short in capturing these", "score": 0.5300668, "raw_content": "![Moonlight Logo](/images/moonlight-logo.png)\n![Moonlight Logo](/images/moonlight-logo.png)\n![Moonlight Logo](/images/moonlight-logo.png)\n\n# [Literature Review] LASER: An LLM-based ASR Scoring and Evaluation Rubric\n\nThe paper introduces LASER (LLM-based ASR Scoring and Evaluation Rubric), a novel metric designed to address the limitations of traditional Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) evaluation metrics like Word Error Rate (WER). WER often unfairly penalizes morphologically and syntactically diverse errors that do not significantly alter the semantic meaning of a sentence. This issue is particularly pronounced in morphologically rich Indian languages, where WER struggles with inflectional variants, compound word representations (e.g., `paas wala` vs. `paaswala`), alternate transliterations (e.g., `ayskrim` vs. `aaiskrim`), colloquialisms, abbreviations, and numerical phrases. Existing semantic metrics like BERTScore or SemDist, and phonetic metrics like PER, also fall short in capturing these linguistic nuances while assigning appropriate penalties.\n\n`paas wala`\n`paaswala`\n`ayskrim`\n`aaiskrim`\n\nLASER leverages the in-context learning capabilities of Large Language Models (LLMs) to provide a nuanced evaluation. The core methodology involves a carefully designed scoring rubric that classifies ASR transcription errors into three categories:\n\n`sundar`\n`sundar`\n`na`\n\nThe sentence-level LASER score is calculated using the formula:\n$\\text{Score} = 1 - \\frac{\\text{Total penalty}}{\\text{Number of reference words}}$\nwhere `Total penalty` is the sum of penalties (0 for no-penalty errors, 0.5 for minor, 1 for major) for all mismatches, and `Number of reference words` is the word count of the original reference sentence.\n\n`Total penalty`\n`Number of reference words`\n\nThe core of LASER's implementation lies in a meticulously crafted prompt provided to state-of-the-art LLMs. This prompt consists of three main components:\n(a) **Detailed Instructions:** Guiding the LLM to tokenize sentences, align ground-truth with predictions, identify mismatches, classify them by error type using examples, assign penalties, and finally compute the sentence-level LASER score.\n(b) **Detailed Examples:** Providing an example for every error type listed in Table 1, primarily in Hindi (Devanagari script) within an English (Latin script) prompt.\n(c) **Step-by-Step Reasoning (Chain-of-Thought):** Instructing the LLM to return its response in a structured format: `(Word count of original sentence; list of non-penalizable errors; list of major penalizable errors; list of minor penalizable errors; total penalty; score)`. This ensures consistent application of the metric.\n\n`(Word count of original sentence; list of non-penalizable errors; list of major penalizable errors; list of minor penalizable errors; total penalty; score)`\n\nThe system was evaluated using a subset of the IndicVoices test set, encompassing Hindi, Marathi (Indo-Aryan), Malayalam, and Kannada (Dravidian) languages, with ASR predictions generated by SeamlessM4T. Human annotators, provided with the same instructions and examples, generated ground-truth penalty scores for correlation analysis.\n\n**Key Results:**\n\n**Limitations:**\nLLMs can exhibit inferential inconsistencies across different runs, especially for lower-resource languages. The prompt-based approach also introduces higher latency compared to traditional metrics. Finetuning helps address inconsistency by fixing model weights and improving efficiency.\n\nThe paper concludes that LASER offers a robust, fine-grained ASR evaluation metric that aligns closely with human perceptions of error severity, effectively accounting for linguistic and morphological complexities, particularly in Indic languages. The demonstrated cross-lingual transferability and the potential for efficient finetuning using smaller LLMs highlight its scalability and practical utility.\n\n![Moonlight Logo](/images/moonlight-logo.png)\n\nCorca, Inc. / CEO Younghyun Chung / Business Registration Number 271-86-02206\n\n6F, 11-8 Teheran-ro 77-gil, Gangnam-gu, Seoul, Republic of Korea, 06159\n\nContact 02-6925-6978 E-mail: moonlight@corca.ai\n\n© 2026 Corca, Inc. All rights reserved."}, {"url": "https://www.mdpi.com/2227-9032/14/10/1333", "title": "Automatic Speech Recognition in Healthcare in the Post-LLM Era", "content": "criteria from 384 screened records. Administrative documentation was the most common application (42.1%), followed by diagnosis, therapy, and doctor–patient communication. Whisper dominated ASR (52.6%), typically paired with GPT-family or LLaMA-family LLMs in frozen configurations steered through prompting. LLMs served as the primary component in 68.4% of studies. ASR evaluation within the reviewed studies predominantly relied on word error rate, while LLM evaluation remains fragmented with no standard metric. Studies reported documentation time reductions of 30–90%, though privacy reporting was inconsistent, equity concerns were rarely tested systematically, and only five studies provided replication packages. Conclusions: LLM-based ASR shows potential for reducing documentation burden [...] Evaluation Metrics. Eleven of the 19 studies reported ASR-specific evaluation metrics, while 17 reported LLM evaluation metrics. Table 8 summarizes the metrics identified across both components, grouped by metric family, with references to the studies employing each metric. Detailed descriptions of all reported metrics are provided in Appendix A.\n\nTable 8. Evaluation metrics identified across the 19 included studies, grouped by metric family and pipeline component. Frequency indicates the number of studies using each metric. [...] Human-in-the-Loop Evaluation. The extent of human involvement in evaluation differed markedly between the ASR and LLM stages, as shown in Figure 10. For ASR, only four studies (21.1%) incorporated human evaluators [45,46,47,61], typically through manual transcript correction to establish gold-standard references against which automated metrics were computed. Seven studies evaluated ASR without human involvement, and eight did not evaluate ASR at all.\n\nImage 28: Healthcare 14 01333 g010. LLM outputs are far more likely to involve human evaluators (73.7%) than ASR transcriptions (21.1%).", "score": 0.50285697, "raw_content": "Loading [MathJax]/jax/output/HTML-CSS/jax.js\n\n Next Article in Journal\n\n[The Association Between Kinesiophobia and Level of Mobilization in Patients After Open-Heart Surgery](https://www.mdpi.com/2227-9032/14/10/1334)\n\n Previous Article in Journal\n\n[Illness Representations and Quality of Life Among Informal Cancer Caregivers: Examining the Role of Social Support](https://www.mdpi.com/2227-9032/14/10/1330)\n\n## Journals\n\n[Active Journals](https://www.mdpi.com/about/journals)[Find a Journal](https://www.mdpi.com/about/journalfinder)[